A Practical Primer on Processing Semantic Property Norm Data

Erin M. Buchanan, Simon De Deyne, & Maria Montefinese

11/13/2019

What is the property norm task?

  • Participants are given a list of cue words and asked to list properties of those cue words
  • Largely influential data for studying semantic representation and meaning, calculating various measures of similarity, feature informativeness, significance, and richness
  • Standardized stimuli are very useful!

Examples of the property norm task

Examples of the property norm task

Why should we automate data processing?

  • Reproducibility, Openness, Transparency
  • Allow for different processing approaches on the same data
  • Reduced load on lab collecting data

Spelling and Other Text Considerations

  • Remove double letters and other text speech finalllllyyyyy (stringr)
  • Remove contractions and other symbols (textclean)
  • Spell check the data (hunspell)
Example Spelling Dictionary
Spelling Error Suggestion
flys fly
transportaion transportation
firey fiery
neccessety necessity
cigerate refrigerate
dont font

Lemmatization

  • Stemming versus lemmatization (tm vs korPus or textstem)
  • TreeTagger can be difficult to set up, but presents many language models
  • If you are willing to mix and match with python, spacyr is the R wrapper for spaCy
Lemma and Part of Speech (POS) Information from TreeTagger
Cue Feature POS Lemma
airplane is verb be
airplane fast adverb fast
airplane they pronoun they
airplane are verb be
airplane expensive adjective expensive
airplane they pronoun they

Stopwords

  • You guys know what stopwords are
  • Should we remove stopwords?
  • However, one should be explicit about their removal of stopwords because:
    • stopwords(): includes ~ 175
    • tm(): options for nearly 600 words
## [1] "i"      "me"     "my"     "myself" "we"     "our"
## [1] "a"         "a's"       "able"      "about"     "above"     "according"

Processing Type

  • Multiword sequences: if you collect data in a practical way, you would simply use the finalized clean version of the data to combine for analysis
    • Stopwords may allow of fuzzy matching for ontology labels
  • Bag of Words approach: tidytext presents many great functions for grouping and combining lemmas to create cue-feature lists

Finalized Data

  • Idiosyncratic responses: by providing the complete feature lists, one may decide what level of response is necessary for their project

Does it work?

  • Correlation with MEN dataset ratings is rs .54 (multiword) and .70 (bag of worlds)
  • Positive agreement with previous analysis of this dataset
